Expected behavior: nextGeneration([[0,0],[0,1],[0,2]]) should return [[-1,1],[0,1],[1,1]] (order doesn't matter)
Current error: Expected [[-1,1],[0,1],[1,1]], received [[0,1]] - missing two cells that should be born via reproduction
Implementation file: src/game-of-life.ts

Current implementation:
```typescript
const countLiveNeighbors = (x: number, y: number, alive: Set<string>): number => {
  let count = 0;
  for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
    for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
      if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
      if (alive.has(`${x + dx},${y + dy}`)) count++;
    }
  }
  return count;
};

export const nextGeneration = (liveCells: number[][]): number[][] => {
  const alive = new Set(liveCells.map(([x, y]) => `${x},${y}`));

  return liveCells.filter(([x, y]) => {
    const neighbors = countLiveNeighbors(x, y, alive);
    return neighbors >= 2 && neighbors <= 3;
  });
};
```

The implementation currently only handles survival (filtering live cells). It needs to also handle reproduction: dead cells adjacent to live cells that have exactly 3 live neighbors should become alive. The `countLiveNeighbors` helper can be reused.

EXPERIMENT MODE: Run autonomously, proceed to Refactor after completion.

